Sure! Here are two monad examples, one in JavaScript and one in C#:

JavaScript:

```
// Example of the Maybe monad in JavaScript
class Maybe {
  constructor(value) {
    this.value = value;
  }
  static of(value) {
    return new Maybe(value);
  }
  map(fn) {
    return this.value ? Maybe.of(fn(this.value)) : Maybe.of(null);
  }
  join() {
    return this.value || Maybe.of(null);
  }
  chain(fn) {
    return this.map(fn).join();
  }
}
```

C#:

```
// Example of the Maybe monad in C#
public class Maybe<T>
{
    private readonly T _value;

    private Maybe(T value)
    {
        _value = value;
    }

    public static Maybe<T> Some(T value) => new Maybe<T>(value);
    public static Maybe<T> None => new Maybe<T>(default(T));

    public TValue Match<TValue>(Func<T, TValue> some, Func<TValue> none) =>
        _value == null ? none() : some(_value);

    public void Match(Action<T> some, Action none) =>
        _value == null ? none() : some(_value);

    public Maybe<TResult> Select<TResult>(Func<T, TResult> selector) =>
        _value == null ? Maybe<TResult>.None : Maybe<TResult>.Some(selector(_value));

    public Maybe<TResult> SelectMany<TResult>(Func<T, Maybe<TResult>> selector) =>
        _value == null ? Maybe<TResult>.None : selector(_value);
}
```

Here's the min-max normalization function in Go:


```go
package main

import (
	"errors"
	"fmt"
	"math"
)

func minMaxNormalization(arr []float64, providedMin *float64, providedMax *float64) ([]float64, error) {
	if len(arr) == 0 {
		return nil, errors.New("Input array cannot be empty")
	}

	var minVal, maxVal float64
	if providedMin != nil && providedMax != nil {
		if *providedMin == *providedMax {
			return nil, errors.New("Provided minimum and maximum values cannot be equal")
		}
		minVal, maxVal = *providedMin, *providedMax
	} else {
		minVal, maxVal = arr[0], arr[0]
		for _, val := range arr {
			if val < minVal {
				minVal = val
			}
			if val > maxVal {
				maxVal = val
			}
		}
	}

	if minVal == maxVal {
		return nil, errors.New("Input array must have at least two distinct values")
	}

	normalizedArr := make([]float64, len(arr))
	for i, val := range arr {
		normalizedArr[i] = (val - minVal) / (maxVal - minVal)
	}

	return normalizedArr, nil
}

func main() {
	arr := []float64{2, 4, 6, 8, 10}
	normalizedArr, err := minMaxNormalization(arr, nil, nil)
	if err != nil {
		fmt.Println(err)
	} else {
		fmt.Println(normalizedArr)
	}

	minVal, maxVal := 0.0, 12.0
	normalizedArr2, err := minMaxNormalization(arr, &minVal, &maxVal)
	if err != nil {
		fmt.Println(err)
	} else {
		fmt.Println(normalizedArr2)
	}
}
```

This Go function has the same functionality as the Python one you provided. It takes an input array and optional minimum and maximum values. If the minimum and maximum values are not provided, it calculates them from the input array. Then, it performs min-max normalization using the specified or calculated minimum and maximum values.

in C++ "&" has multiple meanings.

If it is used on an existing variable it will return its adress that can be assigned to a pointer. This is useful because by using a pointer you are able to refence a variable outside of the current scope and have side effect on it. Here is an example:
   void f (string* s){
      *s="new string";
   }
   int main(){
     string s = "old string";
     cout<<s<<endl;
     f(&s);
     cout<<s<<endl;
     return 0;
   }
The output will be:
   old string
   new string
This is the same as in C but as we can see is verbose as I need to always dereference the pointer to access the variable.

C++ introduced references that can be used to ease this transferring of variables between scopes. Here is an example of it in action:
   void f(string& s){
     s="new string";
   }
   int main(){
    string s = "old string";
    cout<<s<<endl;
    f(s)
    cout<<s<<endl;
   }
The output will be the same as the code above, but we didn't need to pass the adress and then dereference it.

These methods can also be used to optimize your code: by using pointers or references the program doesn't have to copy the variable onto the stack for the function to access it, it only has to save its address.
C++ 11 has also introduced rvalue references, that can be used to further optimize your code!

